    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"Missing Data\"\nformat:\n  html:\n    css: styles.css\n    embed-resources: TRUE\n    code-fold: true\n    page-layout: full\n    fig_caption: yes\n---\n\n\n\n\n**Questions**\n\n1. **Depending on the state, can we assume that people in prison with missing parole eligibility data who have a sentence length of \"Life, LWOP, Life plus additional years, Death\" are not eligible for parole? Does offense type matter?** For example, in the state of Georgia, 30% of people have missing parole eligibility data. Of these people, 70% had a violent offense and 20% had a Life/LWOP/Death sentence length. Of the people with a Life/LWOP/Death sentence length and missing parole eligibility data, 97% had a violent offense.   \n<br>\n2. **Depending on the state, can we assume that someone is not eligible for parole because they have a short sentence? Is time served so brief that the parole process might not be deemed necessary?** For example, in Georgia, 83% of people with a sentence length of <1 year are missing parole eligibility information.   \n<br>\n3. **Do we need to take into account the prison sentencing system of the state to determine who is potentially eligible or not eligible for parole?** For example, in Georgia,  \"While the grant of parole is discretionary, consideration for parole is often not; most inmates are entitled to automatic consideration for parole. In general, this occurs after serving 1/3 of the total sentence. However, at minimum, a person serving a misdemeanor sentence must serve 6 months and a person serving a felony sentence must serve 9 months. Inmates serving 21 years or more, but not a life sentence, become eligible after serving a 7 year term. In addition, inmates convicted of certain serious crimes (e.g. aggravated assault, incest, drug trafficking) are not eligible for parole until they have served 7 years or 1/3 of the prison term, whichever comes first.\"  \n<br>\n[Word document](https://csgorg.sharepoint.com/:w:/s/Team-JC-Research/EZCeIZ0UTgNCu9aCZ4eXqpYBsHeh_ETS4EM3a-nOJmB5Cg?e=BXUemM) in Sharepoint for discussing missingness.  \n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n:::\n\n\n<br>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n**Parole Eligibility Status by Sentence Length**\n\nData: NCRP year-end population  \n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div class=\"reactable html-widget html-fill-item-overflow-hidden html-fill-item\" id=\"htmlwidget-54bd5416109cd3bfdec4\" style=\"width:auto;height:auto;\"></div>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-54bd5416109cd3bfdec4\">{\"x\":{\"tag\":{\"name\":\"Reactable\",\"attribs\":{\"data\":{\"state\":[\"Alabama\",\"Alaska\",\"Arkansas\",\"California\",\"Colorado\",\"Connecticut\",\"Delaware\",\"Florida\",\"Georgia\",\"Hawaii\",\"Illinois\",\"Indiana\",\"Iowa\",\"Kansas\",\"Kentucky\",\"Louisiana\",\"Maine\",\"Maryland\",\"Massachusetts\",\"Minnesota\",\"Mississippi\",\"Missouri\",\"Montana\",\"Nebraska\",\"Nevada\",\"New Hampshire\",\"New York\",\"North Carolina\",\"North Dakota\",\"Ohio\",\"Oklahoma\",\"Oregon\",\"Pennsylvania\",\"Rhode Island\",\"South Carolina\",\"South Dakota\",\"Tennessee\",\"Texas\",\"Utah\",\"Vermont\",\"Virginia\",\"Washington\",\"West Virginia\",\"Wisconsin\",\"Wyoming\"],\"sentlgth_category\":[\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years\",\"1-24.9 years